annotation.TEXT: Alright, now to take off and get that star I saw up in the air.
Like that one! Also, I saw yet another midair star!
I'm not sure if I'm heading where I'm supposed to go, or what. I'll just keep going this way, I guess.
I did see another midair star back there. Let's see if I can find a runway that I can take off from.
Yeah, this is time-consuming, and maybe I should've sped up the footage here.
Okay, just up ahead are, in my opinion, the two trickiest stars in the level.
Oh, the screen stopped scrolling down, so this is the bottom of the level.
From here, jump and hover to the right.
Also, I got the perfect. Interestingly, I finished with exactly 100 seconds left on the clock.
I'll check that pipe in a moment.
Oh, man. Another split path. Let's call this one Morton's Fork. (The up/down choice at the beginning shall henceforth be known as Iggy's Fork.)
There's another midair star here.
That looks like a runway I can take off from.
Okay, first of all, if you drill through those bricks next to you at the start, you die, as there's nothing but a bottomless pit that way.
Yep, there's stars and pipes in the lower-right corner of the map here.
Hi, Koakuma! Bye, Koakuma!
BTW, there's another star even higher than that, but it's unreachable from here. I'll get to it later.
Next, I grab this midair star, then try to grab another one to the left. But, if I miss either one, there are runways that I can take off from below.
Okay, right away, I appear to have a choice of going up or down. Let's start by climbing up. And, I can see parts of other nearby chambers. Is this a maze-like level?
Wow, a checkpoint already? But, I'm probably not meant to reach it quite yet. Although, it looks like sequence breaking might just be possible there with the broom.
Yeah... Those took me a while to find. Also, I just realized I forgot two others earlier, not long after the checkpoint. No big deal, since I'm headed that way again.
Whew! (The reason for duck jumping is to have a prayer of slipping through the opening just below the target ledge if you barely miss. I did make it that way one time.)
And then, just climb back up through the level one more time.
Maybe that pipe leads there.
Then, duck jump, bounce high off the guy, and broom hover to the left to hopefully make it!
Oh, nice. A broom. However, that probably means I'll have to do some flying for some stars... I'd better be careful not to lose it.
Yep, those two are easy to miss as well, although I found them fairly early on in my level-scouring.
If I take too much time exploring earlier parts without first getting a good idea of how long the level is, I might risk running out of time.
Now, this took me I think a couple of hours of scouring the level to find every last star. I've come up with a specific route that I like to take to help keep me from forgetting any.
To be continued... Ze!
Oh, hey. The falling broom was still there. I wonder if power ups ever despawn from just simply going too far off screen, even if they don't go out of bounds...
Fortunately, there's nothing as insane as the end of 2-2-1. There are certain stars that are on the tricky side, though. I'll mention them when I reach them.
Okay, now I should have 80 stars before drilling through the bricks above the goal, but I only have 79. So, where's the star I'm missing?
Got 'em. Now, should I continue down that way, or maybe try going to the right? ...I'll go right.
D'oh. Missed that one, which I should've actually gotten earlier. No big deal. It's easy to get by jumping from the pipe on the right and hovering.
I'm flying here to remove any chance of screwing up this jump.
Let's begin 2-2-2, on Tuesday! But, without tutus, unfortunately.
Just spotted another star up in the air. This is gonna be a thing in this level, isn't it?
Okay, I can go down from here, or fly upwards. Let's call this Lemmy's Fork.
Well, you take off from the upper-right corner of the level, then hover as best you can to the left, and hope that you eventually see the star.
Nope, it's another broom. Well, I'll keep that in mind for later.
Also, I did indeed notice the stars to the left of this runway, but I'm thinking I might be coming back there later.
Wow, that was hilariously crazy! Anyway, it is actually just barely possible to run back and forth to take off in that 8-tile space.
There's a P block and some stars. That P block probably contains another broom, but who knows? It might be meat. We haven't seen bootleg Yoshi in a while.
Also, be careful not to get hit. There is one replacement broom in the second half of this level, but if you get hit before reaching the checkpoint, you may want to just restart.
Whoa, whoops!
Okay, I could just drill through one whole column quickly here. But I'm going to carefully drill away both columns, in case I want to backtrack this way later.
And, I've landed who knows where, but there's another star in this brick.
Actually, I don't know much about tacos, but I do wonder where Taco Bell gets the "Bell" in its name from.
Yes, I did miss a couple stars in bricks below. I intend to come back to them later, time permitting.
Can't enter that pipe either.
Be very careful as you drill these bricks here. There's nothing but bottomless pit directly below them (I think).
Ugh, I can't hit that one brick with my broom from this side.
I wasn't expecting to accidentally break through a brick there, and in my surprise, I accidentally hit Alt again, this time actually opening up the Alt menu.
Oh, hey. It's that checkpoint I saw much earlier. Now, I could easily backtrack for the other paths I didn't take at this point, but I kind of want to keep going upwards for now.
Good thing I didn't accidentally close the game or anything. Anyway, take off from here to find one star high in the sky.
ERGH!!! ...Nope, I can't "ERGH!!!" enough to reach those stars. I'll have to bounce off of a duder to get them. At least there are a couple just below me that I can use...
Or, maybe tacos made good hearing aids or something.
Oh, man. Star over there. But, what's below?
Okay, at this point, I should have 25 stars with my route, and I do. Next, take off from here and grab two midair stars a bit to the right.
Maybe there's some sort of relation to Alexander Graham Bell? Perhaps they used tacos as makeshift telephones back in the old days somehow.
Okay, I remember this spot, which had a single brick with a star in it.
So, next time, another boss level, which I think will involve another bird-like opponent.
I saw another midair star, and since this enclosed space is 10 tiles long, I'm sure I can run back and forth to take off from here, since I learned earlier that 9 is enough.
I guess I'll keep going this way, even though I know there's stuff to the left that I missed.
Yeah, actually reaching the stars is simple, but getting back alive isn't. So, place the stunned duder down carefully, and wait for him to wake up.
Oh, I hit the right edge of the level here, so maybe I'm nearing the end.
And whoops! I hit the goal suddenly right there! Aww... I wasn't really done exploring yet, but it's nice to know that I reached the goal without dying or even getting hit.
I think they ended up dominating the toy industry at the time, and were called "Dominating Tacos", or "Dominos" for short.
Man, this level just keeps going...
I like to fly just to carefully drop onto this single block here, just to be safer.
So, I think this run won't be an attempt at 100%, but I'll try to get a feel for what's where as I go along.
Anyway, that's the story of how tacos saved Christmas. The End.
NOTE: If you get hit and want the 2nd broom here, you need to toss a duder straight up at the block from down below, as you can't reach the block yourself without flying.
Oh, I saw another star up there.
Hello, and welcome back to Super Marisa World! Last time, I had to do tricky broom hovering over spikes. Let's hope the next level doesn't have anything that tricky...
At this point, I like to go left, like I did on my first run.
Okay, now drill through these bricks. (But, DO NOT continue holding down, or you WILL fall straight into a bottomless pit directly below the bricks.)
Well, remember earlier, when I said that there was a higher-up star near the left side of the level that I couldn't reach by flying at it from below?
Obviously, be careful with grabbing the six stars in those bricks.
Yep. Note that back-and-forth running like that is only effective if you're hitting walls to turn around. If you skid to a stop without a wall, or you jump, all built-up speed is lost.
Okay, now for a couple of cleverly hidden stars... Fly/hover DOWN from here.
Now, just like I did the first time, I want to run back and forth to fly for the star above here.
Or, maybe that pipe leads nowhere. (It could be an exit pipe from elsewhere, though.)
No, wait. What am I talking about? Tacos were more fun to line up in a row, so that when you knocked over the first one, it would knock over the next one, and so on.
Bingo! That was the very last star I found during the level-scouring phase. (Thank goodness I didn't have to be absolutely perfect with the broom hovering, but man...)
But, if I did that, I wouldn't have time to talk about tacos!
Let's go down from Lemmy's Fork now. I'll do so carefully.
There's those two stars I said I'd be back for later, and whoops, I fell! But, by holding right...

More stars over here.

Stun a duder, and carry him with you as you drop down here.

Oh, BTW, just to the right of the bottom of this brick column is the goal.
77 is a nice number, but it's no 100. Now, let's go back and try for that perfect...

24 attempts later...
Then, get these 5 stars on this platform with the 2 duders.

Yet another pipe I can't enter.
So, after that, I like to get those two stars as you just saw, and then head to the right.
